State is a timely collection that examines the controversial role of the state as a promoter of gambling activities often against the best interest of its citizens. Investigating the tensions that arise from the relationships between gambling and morality, risk, social policy, crime, and youth problem gambling, these essays draw upon a range of disciplines to consider the economic benefits and social costs of legalized gambling. A contemporary study that raises important questions about state conduct, precarious policy issues, public health, and addictions, Casino State provides a necessary and comprehensive overview of the central issues related to the legalization and expansion of gambling in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGamblingxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aGamblingxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aGamblingzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBadgley, Kerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Colin S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosgrave, James F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDerevensky, Jeffrey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartnagel, Timothy F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlassen, Thomas R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlassen, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMacneil, Ray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcMillen, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamp, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Garry J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWynne, Harold, econtrib